:"Rotherfield Peppard, Oxfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pipard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Marcel, Normand, Emile, Antoine, Cecile, Jean-Paul, Renald, Adrien, Aime, Andre, Aurel.","French:","nickname from Old French <i>pinard</i>, a small medieval coin, so named from <i>pin</i> ‘pine’ because it bore the device of a pine cone."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Pipard I was born about 1118, in Rotherfield Peppard, Oxfordshire, England, his father, Gilbert Pipard I, was 50 and his mother, Alice de Romiley, was 46. He had at least 5 sons with Joan of Devon. He died from 1167 to 1169, in Oxfordshire, England."},"et":{"about 1118–Between 1167 and 1169":"umbes 1118–1167 kuni 1169","1118–1169":"1118–1169","1114–Female":"1114–Surnud","1133–1194":"1133–1194","1136–1185":"1136–1185","1144–1192":"1144–1192","–1190":"–1190","1070–1118":"1070–1118","1074–1137":"1074–1137","1190":"1190","1185":"1185","1074":"1074","1194":"1194","1192":"1192","1070":"1070","1118":"1118","after 1118":"pärast 1118","1137":"1137","about 1118":"umbes 1118","1136":"1136","1114":"1114","1169":"116